  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused when an object travels through the air at a speed greater than the speed of sound, which is approximately 343 meters per second (1,125 feet per second) at sea level under standard conditions. Here\u2019s how it happens:\n\n1. **Sound Waves**: Sound travels in waves through the air. When an object is moving slower than the speed of sound, these waves can move ahead of it, allowing the sound to be heard as it approaches.\n\n2. **Mach Barrier**: When an object accelerates to the speed of sound, it compresses the sound waves in front of it, creating a buildup of pressure. This is often referred to as reaching \"Mach 1.\"\n\n3. **Shock Waves**: Once the object surpasses the speed of sound (Mach 1), it creates shock waves. These waves are generated because the object is moving faster than the sound waves it produces. The shock waves coalesce into a cone shape called a \"Mach cone\" that trails behind the object.\n\n4. **Boom**: As the shock wave passes an observer on the ground, it produces a sudden change in pressure, creating the loud sound known as a sonic boom. This can sound like an explosion or thunderclap.\n\nSonic booms can be disruptive and are often associated with high-speed aircraft, especially military jets. The intensity and impact of a sonic boom depend on several factors, including the size and speed of the object, as well as its altitude.",
